Asphalt UNAM avoid potholes
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry, UNAM, develops polymer-modified asphalt to produce a mixture with better performance regardless of environmental conditions and temperature
If the signals sent by the pavement were addressed, it would be necessary to repair about 200 thousand potholes each rainy season in the Metropolitan Area of ​​Mexico, Najera said Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (CF) of the UNAM, who said that if the process of construction and maintenance of an asphalt pavement is adequate, the bumps could be reduced in quantity or even eliminated.
In his lecture A technological review of the bumps, issued under the International Year of Chemistry, announced that the laboratory in charge of developing polymer-modified asphalt to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to asphalt, but with a greater mechanical strength, both at high and at low temperatures.
Nájera Herrera felt that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, as some cities in the north of the country to improve its performance and, therefore, the formation of potholes.
He explained that the asphalt, the heavier oil is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, a high molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and other low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the floor its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of asphalt is that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, it behaves as a liquid at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very high as 50 degrees Celsius has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that the resistance of asphalt streets is not uniform, but is modified during the day according to temperature and environmental conditions, said the specialist in chemical engineering.
The researcher observed that CF the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible pavement, which consists of six layers of materials, of which the last three involve the asphalt.
Among the more superficial layers is the asphalt, composed of small stones dipped in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the stones which is the folder, he said, is bathed with asphalt.
When driving vehicles and generated efforts, it allows the forces are spread very well on the pavement.
If it were modified asphalt would spread even better, said chemical engineer.
On the asphalt, he added, place a final layer folder called rolling, which is made of a fine stone material, ie sand also bathes in asphalt.
Since this is the layer that will be in contact with the tires of vehicles, must have more mechanical strength than asphalt and provide friction on the road.
As part of the pavement that is to receive and disseminate efforts, rolling folder also requires having the right thickness and must care for the material it is made.
The weather, especially humidity and temperature variations are also an important factor to consider, especially water, he said, because it affects considerably the performance of the asphalt.
When the soil is wetted, water diffuses into the interior of the folder and is difficult to leave, this causes a softening of all layers of the pavement and therefore, the formation of bumps.
In the process of forming a bump, he said, the first to wear the film is rolling and is affected only after the asphalt, but the damage does not happen instantly, but a process that should be addressed at the first signs with appropriate maintenance programs.
Also a member of the National System of Researchers explained that the vehicle load is another important factor in the formation of potholes and, therefore, the thickness of each layer of the pavement should be provided in relation to vehicle load and ensure meets, to avoid the formation of bumps frequently.
Rafael Herrera said that there is still much to investigate and work on the asphalt, for example, asphalt emulsions, which in other countries are already on the market and even help repair potholes with ease and without using high temperatures.
