The Nord Stream, new front door for Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline, which connects directly to Western Europe with Russia through the Baltic Sea bottom has already been commissioned.
Gas be supplied to meet the needs of thirty million homes.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with great pomp.
On Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four heads of State and Government, participated on the Baltic, between the music of the orchestra and a fine buffet, at the opening of Nord Stream, the new pipeline that connects directly under Sea, Russia and Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, Prime Minister Francois Fillon and his counterpart from the Netherlands, Mark Rutte, together have turned the wheel of the valve that controls the entry of Russian gas network Western Europe.
With this new pipeline will arrive each year 27.5 million cubic meters of additional Russian gas to Western Europe through the first was of 1,224 miles that connect the region of St. Petersburg in Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second tube should be completed in late 2012 that will provide a total of 55,000 million cubic meters of gas, ie, enough to cover the French consumption.
In addition, there is already talk of the possibility of building a third tube by the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge work presents an air of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries had strongly opposed the project.
In fact, the Nord Stream will allow supply gas directly to Germany, avoiding over land by third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
Suddenly, these two countries lose some of their power: for them, will be more difficult to influence Russia threatening to block his access to the markets of Western Europe.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream as a &quot;new Germano-Soviet pact,&quot; referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of European energy, since the project has created a gap between the European East and West.
Russia has managed, in just five years, to succeed his vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, large consumers of gas and with reserves dwindling.
&quot;This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that organically unites us,&quot; confirmed François Fillon at the opening of the pipeline, demonstrating how big contracts in the gas sector are as politically and economically.
All this explains the broad smiles on the faces of the directors of Gazprom, many in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The tube is made of steel submarine cement coated to protect against ship anchors.
It rests on the seabed, at an average depth of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating from World War II.
&quot;It was necessary to remove or destroy a hundred of them, as a precaution,&quot; said Jens Müller, spokesman for the company Nord Stream.
It also became necessary extreme measures of protection of fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake weighs 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted along its length, either by valves, or for maintenance stations.
He provided a control platform in Swedish waters, but the project leaders renounced it to see that the Swedes were unwilling to allow a Russian state company was established permanently in the sea off their coasts.
&quot;In case of failure, interrupt the flow of gas in less than a minute,&quot; says Jens Müller.
In case of leakage, the gas pipeline is released, therefore, to the atmosphere.
But the builders considered unlikely that a leak occurs, as planned joints that are projected to have a flight every 100,000 years.
State control of the pipeline is ensured by a robot submarine, carried by a ship, which carries out inspections outside and through a device that circulates inside the pipeline.
With a pure form, is introduced inside the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
On arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, to provide accurate records possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline is designed to run for fifty years without any servicing.
Gas circulation is ensured simply by pressure.
The top is 200 bars and 100 bars output.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader is Gazprom, which holds 51% stake.
She joined the German E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), and the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture, called Nord Stream, responsible for building and operating the pipeline.
Headquartered in Zug, Switzerland, where the imposition is particularly favorable.
Then that company Gazprom rented for a period of twenty-five years renewable, the total transport capacity of gas.
&quot;A Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transport,&quot; says Jens Müller.
The financing of the pipeline construction has been carried out by 30% with the contribution of the shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work should reach 7,400 million euros for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are assured that their investment will not exceed, as Gazprom alone assumes the risk of the expenses.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic Lubmin, on a sandy coast planted pines.
Valves, with 4.5 meters high, form the output port of the gas.
There are sensors that measure pressure, temperature and the specific characteristics of gas on arrival, before being transferred to the German gas pipeline.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives a million cubic meters of Russian gas per hour.
At full capacity, will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
